{"cursor":"17060","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":", shown here in a powder form.]]\n\n'Pectin' (from {{transl|grc|pÄktikÃ³s}}, \"congealed, curdled\" [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-\nbin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3D%2382916 Pektikos, Henry\nGeorge Liddell, Robert Scott, \"A Greek-English Lexicon\", at Perseus] ) is a\nstructural heteropolysaccharide contained in the primary cell walls of\nterrestrial plants. It was first isolated and described in 1825 by Henri\nBraconnot. It is produced commercially as a white to light brown\npowder, mainly extracted from citrus fruits, and is used in food as a gelling\nagent particularly in jams and jellies. It is also used in fillings, medicines,\nsweets, as a stabilizer in fruit juices and milk drinks, and as a source of\ndietary fiber.\n","linknr":276,"url":"Pectin","recorded":1362373046,"links":52,"instances":["fruit","fruit","nutrition","chemistry","botany"],"pdf":["http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/site/en/consleg/1995/L/01995L0002-20031120-en.pdf"],"categories":["Polysaccharides","Food additives","Food science","Cell biology","Edible thickening agents","Demulcents"],"headings":["Biology","Chemistry","Sources and production","Uses","Legal status","History","Market Information","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/d/dd/Pectin.jpg/220px-Pectin.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Foods.jpg/19px-Foods.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["petiole","botany"],["prebiotic","nutrition"],["syneresis","chemistry"],["apple","fruit"],["orange","fruit"]],"members":["apple","orange","prebiotic","syneresis","petiole"],"related":["Heteropolysacch